Lets take a look at the MPG dataset.This dataset contains a subset of the fuel economy data that the EPA makes available on http://fueleconomy.gov. It contains only models which had a new release every year between 1999 and 2008 - this was used as a proxy for the popularity of the car.

Explore the data to see whats in there

data("mpg")

Run the code to make a graph

ggplot(data = mpg, aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
    geom_point()

Add color, size, alpha, and shape aesthetics to your graph. Experiment.

ggplot(data = mpg, aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
    geom_point(aes(size = cyl,
                   color = manufacturer,
                   alpha = cty,
                   shape = class))
## Warning: The shape palette can deal with a maximum of 6 discrete values because
## more than 6 becomes difficult to discriminate; you have 7. Consider
## specifying shapes manually if you must have them.
## Warning: Removed 62 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

ggplot(data = mpg, aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
    geom_point(size = 3,
               color = "blue",
               alpha = 0.5,
               shape = 11)

Replace this scatterplot with one that draws boxplots. Use the cheatsheet. Try your best guess.

ggplot(mpg, aes(x = class, y = hwy)) + 
    geom_boxplot()

Make the histogram of the hwy variable.Hint: Do not supply a y variable.

ggplot(mpg, aes(x = hwy)) +
    geom_histogram(binwidth = 5)

Make a density plot of hwy colored by class. Use the cheatsheet and/or try your best guess.

ggplot(mpg, aes(x = hwy, color = class)) +
    geom_density()

Make the bar chart of class.

ggplot(mpg, aes(x = class)) +
    geom_bar()

Predict what this code will do. Then run it.

ggplot(mpg, aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
    geom_point() +
    geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'
